messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

[
  {
    "path": "/api/account",
    "handler": "UserAccountController",
    "implementationPresent": true,
    "isPrefix": true,
    "pathFromLiteral": true,
    "pathFromConvention": false,
    "isRest": true,
    "isTest": false
  },
  {
    "path": "/api/account/{account_id}",
    "handler": "UserAccountController.getUserAccountById",
    "implementationPresent": true,
    "isPrefix": false,
    "pathFromLiteral": true,
    "pathFromConvention": false,
    "isRest": true,
    "isTest": false
  },
  {
    "path": "/api/account/signup",
    "handler": "UserAccountController.signupForNewAccount",
    "implementationPresent": true,
    "isPrefix": false,
    "pathFromLiteral": true,
    "pathFromConvention": false,
    "isRest": true,
    "isTest": false
  }
]

Explanation:
- The file is a Spring @RestController with a class-level @RequestMapping("/api/account"). That class-level mapping is included as an API entry because it binds the "/api/account" path and dispatches to the controller's methods; it is a prefix mapping (isPrefix = true).
- Two method-level mappings are present and use literal strings in annotations:
  - @GetMapping("/{account_id}") composes with the class-level prefix to form "/api/account/{account_id}" and is handled by UserAccountController.getUserAccountById.
  - @PostMapping("/signup") composes with the class-level prefix to form "/api/account/signup" and is handled by UserAccountController.signupForNewAccount.
- All handlers' implementations are present in this same source file. The paths are taken from literal strings in the source code annotations; none are derived from Spring naming conventions. All entries are REST endpoints and none are test-only. 
- No other path mappings are present in this file (private methods are utility methods, not mapped).

path.description: The HTTP request path, which must begin with a forward slash (/) and have path parameters wrapped in curly braces ({}). Set this to null if it cannot be determined.
